{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NuNr1F6CU2Xq1pELMHeu3t","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the problem fully:\n\n1. The ConfigMap `rabbitmq-config` currently has:\n   - `enabled_plugins`: `[rabbitmq_management,rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s,rabbitmq_prometheus].`\n   - `rabbitmq.conf`: includes `prometheus.tcp.port = 15692` and `prometheus.tcp.ip = 0.0.0.0`\n\nBut the actual files inside the pods show:\n   - `enabled_plugins`: `[rabbitmq_management,rabbitmq_peer_discovery_k8s].` (missing `rabbitmq_prometheus`)\n   - `rabbitmq.conf`: missing the prometheus port configuration\n\nThe issue is that the ConfigMap was recently updated with the prometheus settings, but since it's mounted using `subPath`, Kubernetes doesn't automatically propagate those changes to the running pods. The `subPath` mount creates a direct bind that freezes the configuration at pod creation time, so the pods are still running the older version without prometheus enabled. They need to be restarted to pick up the new configuration.\n\nTo fix this, I'll restart the RabbitMQ StatefulSet using a rollout restart command, which will bring the pods back up one at a time since they use the `OrderedReady` policy. Then I need to update the Prometheus ConfigMap to add scrape targets for all three RabbitMQ instances and reload Prometheus to start collecting metrics. can POST to `/-/reload` to trigger the reload. Since the Prometheus volume is mounted as a directory rather than a subPath, ConfigMap changes will propagate automatically to the pod, but I still need to explicitly reload the configuration.\n\nMy plan is to restart the RabbitMQ StatefulSet first to pick up its new configuration, then update the Prometheus ConfigMap with the RabbitMQ scrape targets, wait for the changes to propagate, and finally trigger the reload endpoint. I need to be mindful of the StatefulSet's OrderedReady policy—it will restart the pods sequentially starting from the highest ordinal.\n\nLooking at the actual port configuration, the StatefulSet spec only declares ports 5672 and 15672, but the headless service already exposes 15692, so DNS resolution should work fine for the metrics endpoint.\n\nThe connection failure I saw earlier was because the prometheus plugin wasn't enabled yet. Once I restart the pods with the updated ConfigMap containing the prometheus plugin and port configuration, 15692 will be available. My approach is to restart the RabbitMQ pods first so they pick up the changes, then update the Prometheus ConfigMap with scrape targets for all three pods using the headless service DNS, and finally reload Prometheus.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":836,"cache_read_input_tokens":35597,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":836},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c6abd31-7a7a-4384-90d1-bce3d6101d15","uuid":"722ec944-5a8f-427c-bebf-8f2a7a4bd94b","request_id":"req_011Cc74PD8CvMohfd4ELoUnJ"}
